      <h2>The Stadiums</h2>
      <p>Click to Expand.</p>
      <div class="innerModule">
        <h3>Luzhuniki Stadium, Moscow</h3>
        <p>Home to the Russian National Team themselves, the <span class="bold">Luzhuniki Stadium</span>, whose name derives from the meadows in the bend of Moskva River where the stadium was built, is a 81,000 seat stadium that will host the opening match of the tournament between hosts Russia and Saudi Arabia, as well as the final.</p>
        <p>Opened in 1956, the stadium was recently renovated in order to prepare it for the World Cup.</p>
        <p>The stadium is no stranger to large events and games, as it hosted the 1980 Summer Olympics and the UEFA Champions League Final in 2008, between English giants Machester United and Chelsea.</p>
        <p>By the end of the tournament, the stadium will join a select group of venues that have hosted a World Cup Final, Summer Olympics, and UEFA Champions League Final.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="innerModule">
        <h3>Saint-Petersburg Stadium, Saint-Petersburg</h3>
        <p>Also known as the <span class="bold">Krestovsky Stadium</span> or <span class="bold">Zenit Arena</span>, is a 67,000 capacity stadium that also serves as home for Russian football club <span class="bold">Zenit St. Petersburg</span>.</p>
        <p>The stadium suffered many setbacks during construction which caused it to be finished behind schedule and well-above budget. Despite this, the stadium was finished in 2017 and the first match played in the newly built stadium was between Zenit St. Petersburg and FC Ural.</p>
        <p>A few months later, the stadium was used in the 2017 Confederations Cup. It was used in a few matches and hosted the final between Germany and Chile.</p>
        <p>The Saint-Petersburg Stadium is set to host plenty of Group Stage matches as well as a semi final in the upcoming World Cup.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="innerModule">
        <h3>Fisht Olympic Stadium, Sochi</h3>
        <p>Originally built for the 2014 Winter Olympics and Paralympics, the <span class="bold">Fisht Stadium</span>, was orignally an enclosed space but changed into an open air staidum in preperation for the 2017 Confederations Cup and the 2018 World Cup.</p>
        <p>With a temporary capacity of about 47,000, the Fisht stadium will host a few group matches as well as a quarter final in the upcoming World Cup</p>
